    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-06T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-06T12:00:00-05:00" n="68"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d68">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EAC/11–644: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The American Representative to the French Provisional
                        Government</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-06T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 6, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 7:24 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>351. Bidault<note n="15" xml:id="d68fn15">Georges Bidault, French Foreign
                        Minister from September 9, 1944.</note> showed me this afternoon very
                    confidentially a note from the Russian Ambassador here<note n="16"
                        xml:id="d68fn16">Alexander Efremovich Bogomolov.</note> setting out that
                    after conversations in regard to the European Advisory Commission with our
                    Government and the British, it had been decided to issue the well-known
                    invitation to Massigli. The Russian Ambassador went on to say that his
                    Government had come to the conclusion that France should be invited to become a
                    permanent member of the Commission and had so communicated to our
                        Government<note n="17" xml:id="d68fn17">Presumably a reference to the Soviet
                        memorandum of October 29, <ref target="#pg_80">p. 80</ref>.</note> and the
                    British but had not yet had a reply in the premises from us or the British.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
